<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>VSO Submission to International Development Select Committee Inquiry into Disability and Development</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:35.45pt"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="100" height="77" alt="" /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">DIS 58 </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">VSO Submission to International Development Select Committee Inquiry into Disability and Development.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">VSO is an international development agency with 55 years’ experience of addressing poverty and disadvantage through our unique approach of working through volunteers. By working closely over time with carefully selected partners – from grassroots organisations to government ministries</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> – </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">volunteers provide the right support to help ensure that local development efforts deliver greatest impact and lasting change</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">. </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">VSO aims to support disabled people to participate as equal members of their families, communities and societies. Volunteers are supporting local agencies and governments to identify strategies that promote disabled people's human rights, such as education, employment and healthcare.  We do this by supporting disabled people's groups to raise awareness of issues that affect disabled people, and working to improve the accessibility and quality of mainstream and special services provided by both the government and by non-governmental organi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ations. </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We welcome the opportunity to submit evidence to this inquiry. VSO is a member of the Global Campaign for Education</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (GCE UK)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, and supports </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">its</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> submission to this inquiry. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">DFID’s commitments on disability </span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We welcome DFID’s recent commitments on disability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to increase access for disabled children to quality education</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. This is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">also an important signal to developing country partners and other donors to prioritise this group in discussions. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Whilst DFID </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">has some examples of good practice in inclusi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ve education</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, we note, along with the Global Campaign for Education</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that the department has no formal framework for the systematic inclusion of disabled people throughout its programmes. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DFID have previously recognised the importance of a “twin-track” approach to disability</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> which sees the active “mainstreaming” or inclusion of disabled people in all aspects of their development work (for example ensuring education programmes support disabled boys and girls), coupled with specific additional inputs and resources which recognise the extreme marginalisation of disabled people and go further in targeting and supporting them.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This approach should now be thoroughly embedded in DFID’s work.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As life expectancies across the world are increasing, there are increasing numbers of people living with disability – particularly in later life. DFID’s health position paper published in July 2013</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> recognises the linkages between disability and poor health outcomes, and in particularly the importance of combating Non Communicable Diseases to prevent greater numbers of people from being affected by disabilities. However, it does not outline how the department proposes to tackle this. Greater consideration needs to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">given to those people who become disabled as result of chronic illness and may sit outside traditional perceptions of “disability”.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A number of barriers exist at the policy, institutional and community levels which can prevent people with disabilities from accessing health, education and other key services .  Action needs to be taken at all of these levels. W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e recommend that disability needs to be recognised as a core development issue by DFID, and all </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">its </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">work should be done through a disability lens. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">O</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ften many </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">disabled </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">people </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">experience </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">multiple discriminations.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> This </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">limits disabled people’s most fundamental rights. Where polling cards are not available in Braille or another accessible format, blind people are denied their right to vote. Where schools have no sign language translation, Deaf people are denied their right to education. Where hospitals do not provide information in simple, accessible ways, people with learning difficulties are denied their right to understand their health or to make decisions about their treatment. Where wells or latrines are physically inaccessible, people with mobility impairments are denied their right to clean water and sanitation</span><span style="color:#231f20; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="color:#231f20; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Challenging discrimination through advocacy and legal frameworks is critical to promoting the rights of disabled people. In Kenya, for example</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> VSO and its partners advocated for the 2013 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">B</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">asic </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ducation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ct to include specific recommendations </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">address the different categories of learn</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> disabilit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">y</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, and to ensure that there are adequate resources available to support </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">these </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">needs.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> DFID should support governments to ensure that legal frameworks and policies make explicit references to improving education provision for children</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">with disabilities.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Promoting Inclusive education </span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DFID should prioritise the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">inclusion of disabled people’s rights </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">into their education programmes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ll programmes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">show how they reach disabled children and young people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">an emphasis throughout on inclusive education that benefits all children.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We support the GCE’s recommendation that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DFID’s recent commitment on accessible school construction should be replicated in other areas of education policy and programmes. DFID is a strong leader in supporting teacher training, which is fundamental </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to improving the quality of education </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">meeting MDG </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">two</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. In order to develop the skills, experience and confidence to be inclusive of all children, teachers need to learn about and practise inclusive education during pre-service and in-service training</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We recommend, along with the GCE,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that DFID should integrate disability and inclusive education throughout the teacher-training it supports</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. This should be done</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in collaboration with national policy-makers, practitioners and other donors. In supporting the participation of disabled people, DFID should also promote the recruitment and retention of disabled teachers including the reasonable adjustments needed in schools for this.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In many countries, unequal access to education is exacerbated by the prevalence of a medical model of disability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. This model </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">perpetuates the notion that disabled children must adapt in order to integrate into mainstream schooling, or be educated in a separate special education system</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he nature of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">children’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">impairments is often poorly understood, resulting in inappropriate service provision. VSO’s experience </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">working on inclusive </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ducation programmes in countries including </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Cambodia, Kenya, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Malawi, Rwanda and Ghana, support</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the arguments of GCE UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">carefully planned and implemented strategies to support the inclusion in mainstream schools is appropriate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the large majority of disabled children</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">enhances the quality of teaching and learning for all children, not just disabled children.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The importance of engaging disabled people in programming </span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DFID</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> recognise</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the vital role </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Disabled People’s Organisations (DPOs) play in development, helping to empower </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">disabled people </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">change attitudes towards disability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. It </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">support</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s this </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">through the Disability Rights Fund. We </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">welcome</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> this and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">support</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the recommendation of the GCE that DFID should place a requirement </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on all its Country Offices to involve DPOs in programme development, implementation and evaluation.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In education</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and health</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, DFID should increase support to facilitate in-count</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ry forums of DPOs, INGOs, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and other</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">CSOs, alongside donors, to support national governments to meet their obligations to deliver education</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and health</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> for all.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">VSO have found that actively involving disabled people changes attitudes towards disability within the community and increases the participation of disabled people in society. Two teams of ICS (International Citizen Service) volunteers – one all-Deaf –ran sessions in schools and communities on preventing sexual abuse of Deaf children, and promoted Deaf culture awareness with teachers and other stakeholder groups in the community. Following a data-profiling exercise of the local Deaf population, conducted by VSO’s volunteers, local partners were able to use the findings to guide the development of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">materials on new Filipino Sign Language terms for interpreting the news and for election advocacy. In the lead up elections in May 2013, the data collection process was used to help to register Deaf people to vote. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The Post 2015 international development process </span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">VSO’s vision for the post 2015 international development framework is one </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">people </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">active partners in development rather than passive beneficiaries of aid; tackles the power imbalances that lie at the heart of inequality and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">marginalisation; and supports the democratic ownership of development agenda</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The UK government should continue to champion the ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">leave no one behind’ </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">principle, the disaggregation of all disability targets alongside other factors, and the principle that targets should only be considered met if for all groups, including disabled people. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We note that data collection is a political, as well as a technical choice. In the words of Hil</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ary Clinton- “what gets </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">measured</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> gets done”. We support the recommendations of the report of the High Level panel for a “data revolution” that will enable the collection of a greater range of both qualitative and quantitative data. We believe that all goals and targets should be monitored using data disaggregated by gender, disability, age, ethnic origin, marital status, sexual orientation and geographic location. This recognises the interaction between different forms of discrimination, and will help to measure the impact of those interactions. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">However, it is important that the data revolution extends to looking at what data is collected, by who and how. Too often, vulnerable people and their priorities are systematically excluded because they are not involved in shaping data collection systems. It is not just the selection of indicators that is important but also who collects the data, where the data comes from, the scale at which the data is collected (i.e. the individual or household level) and how the data is interpreted.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> VSO would like to see the proposed ‘Global Partnership on Development Data’ engage early with CSO who have expertise to share on the current gaps in data, accessibility and the relevance of data sets</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="92" height="344" alt="" style="margin-left:468.95pt; margin-top:-243pt; position:absolute; z-index:-131071" /></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/uk-pledge-to-help-tackle-the-great-neglect-of-disability"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/uk-pledge-to-help-tackle-the-great-neglect-of-disability</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> As defined in, for example, </span><span style="font-fam